@misamsung6191 Sure, but we're not talking about the technology itself here, strictly the design of the blades themselves.  

Also back then, they didn't have the quality of testing equipment we do today, i.e. wind tunnels among many others.  The same testing equipment that, as you so rightly pointed out, helped improve our knowledge and abilities with things like aerodynamics.  Due to that, we can now precisely measure how much wind a particular blade design catches, how much energy loss there is from things like mass of various moving parts, bearing friction, etc.    

As to this design itself though, the mere fact that this blade design has more mass means it is going to produce less as it will require the use of more energy from the wind to spin the heavier prop...all else in the design being equal of course.

@martinrothwell8966 Because drag is a function of speed, particularly in a heavier medium like water.
boat hulls are designed to be efficient at particular speeds. Going above that speed reduces the efficiency, just like driving a car faster than it's designed efficiency. 
This is all 20th century science.

@simonpeggboard4004 Yes, I got it. 

It's worse than any commercial blade design.. the mass distribution, the wobbling, the "pitch inertia", all is worse... as demonstrated by everybody that has bothered to print them and try in their drones. I'm talking about a 75% loss in efficiency, not a joke

It works in boat propellers, cause the fluid dynamics are completely different and cause in water cavitation is a real problem... and as people tend to magical thinking, it was inevitable that some snake oil seller were gonna try to sell the idea for flying applications.
